1
00:00:02,961 --> 00:00:06,211
<i>CHOIR: ♪ The Simpsons ♪</i>

2
00:00:06,297 --> 00:00:08,337
{\an8}HOMER: Oh-hoo-hoo!

3
00:00:08,425 --> 00:00:10,755
{\an8}Pork chops with gravy!

4
00:00:10,844 --> 00:00:13,974
{\an8}Wait... but today's not
Pork Chop Tuesday.

5
00:00:14,055 --> 00:00:15,765
{\an8}Or Gravy Thursday!

6
00:00:15,849 --> 00:00:17,389
{\an8}I also set up some mirrors

7
00:00:17,475 --> 00:00:19,805
{\an8}so you could watch
hockey fights while you eat.

8
00:00:19,894 --> 00:00:21,984
HOMER: Whoo-hoo!

9
00:00:23,314 --> 00:00:27,194
{\an8}Oh, I love Canadian-on-Canadian violence.

10
00:00:27,277 --> 00:00:30,197
{\an8}Oh, baby, this is so great!
Thank you so much.

11
00:00:30,280 --> 00:00:32,820
{\an8}I'm just happy you're happy.

12
00:00:34,325 --> 00:00:37,535
{\an8}Wait a minute, that's not something
people really feel.

13
00:00:37,620 --> 00:00:38,910
{\an8}What's going on?

14
00:00:38,997 --> 00:00:41,117
{\an8}Well, I do have a favor.

15
00:00:41,207 --> 00:00:43,997
{\an8}Patty and Selma came home early
from their vacation,

16
00:00:44,085 --> 00:00:46,375
{\an8}but the cleaners still haven't
gotten all the black mold

17
00:00:46,463 --> 00:00:47,843
{\an8}out of their apartment.

18
00:00:48,673 --> 00:00:49,923
{\an8}(deep roar)

19
00:00:50,008 --> 00:00:52,928
{\an8}So they need a place to stay. Here.

20
00:00:54,095 --> 00:00:55,845
{\an8}-(shrieks)
-Paris was a bust.

21
00:00:55,930 --> 00:00:58,060
{\an8}They wouldn't even let us
see the <i>Mona Lisa.</i>

22
00:00:58,141 --> 00:01:00,351
{\an8}They kept yelling, <i>"La Joconde!</i>

23
00:01:00,435 --> 00:01:02,265
{\an8}Her smile will die!"

24
00:01:02,353 --> 00:01:03,983
{\an8}No, Marge, no!

25
00:01:04,064 --> 00:01:07,194
{\an8}You can't invite a couple of Riddlers
to stay in the Bat Cave!

26
00:01:07,275 --> 00:01:10,065
{\an8}You ate the food
and looked in the mirrors.

27
00:01:10,153 --> 00:01:11,453
{\an8}They're staying!

28
00:01:11,529 --> 00:01:13,529
{\an8}(gruff chuckling)

29
00:01:14,616 --> 00:01:16,616
{\an8}(inhaling, exhaling loudly)

30
00:01:16,701 --> 00:01:19,121
{\an8}(Bart and Lisa coughing)

31
00:01:19,204 --> 00:01:20,294
{\an8}Hmm.

32
00:01:20,371 --> 00:01:23,671
{\an8}Oh, honey,
one teensy problem with this plan.

33
00:01:23,750 --> 00:01:27,550
{\an8}I'm a teensy bit concerned
about them smoking around the children.

34
00:01:27,629 --> 00:01:30,419
{\an8}You know, their lungs are so teensy.

35
00:01:30,507 --> 00:01:31,967
{\an8}Mwah! Mwah!

36
00:01:32,050 --> 00:01:34,050
Hmm. He has a point.

37
00:01:34,135 --> 00:01:36,595
No, no.
No, no, we don't have to smoke.

38
00:01:36,679 --> 00:01:39,019
We can stop whenever we want.
See?

39
00:01:40,266 --> 00:01:42,266
(both grunt)

40
00:01:42,352 --> 00:01:44,272
Okay, how about this--

41
00:01:44,354 --> 00:01:47,194
if you catch us smoking in the house,
even one time,

42
00:01:47,273 --> 00:01:49,323
you can throw us out on the street.

43
00:01:49,400 --> 00:01:52,650
You know what?
I trust them not to smoke.

44
00:01:52,737 --> 00:01:56,027
And if you trust them,
I trust them, too.

45
00:01:57,700 --> 00:01:59,580
(devious chuckle)

46
00:01:59,661 --> 00:02:00,951
Safety first!

47
00:02:01,037 --> 00:02:03,457
Screw this.
We'll just go outside.

48
00:02:03,540 --> 00:02:05,920
Nature is God's ashtray.

49
00:02:06,918 --> 00:02:08,458
(hums)

50
00:02:08,545 --> 00:02:10,255
(thunder crashes)

51
00:02:11,422 --> 00:02:12,882
Bad news, bears.

52
00:02:12,966 --> 00:02:15,426
Forecast calls for nothing but rain.

53
00:02:15,510 --> 00:02:17,260
(both groan)

54
00:02:17,345 --> 00:02:19,425
(grunting)

55
00:02:19,514 --> 00:02:21,274
<i>(glass shatters)</i>

56
00:02:21,349 --> 00:02:23,349
<i>(humming)</i>

57
00:02:24,853 --> 00:02:25,853
<i>(sighs)</i>

58
00:02:28,523 --> 00:02:30,483
Here we go.
Problem solved.

59
00:02:30,567 --> 00:02:32,397
Electric cigarettes.

60
00:02:33,653 --> 00:02:35,033
(loud inhaling)

61
00:02:36,573 --> 00:02:39,163
Choke on our harmless fumes.

62
00:02:40,910 --> 00:02:41,910
Hmm?

63
00:02:41,995 --> 00:02:45,165
Well, if you fall asleep with them,
will you even burn to death?

64
00:02:45,248 --> 00:02:47,248
-BOTH: Uh-uh.
-Oh.

65
00:02:47,333 --> 00:02:49,793
(loud, rapid inhaling and exhaling)

66
00:02:50,879 --> 00:02:52,419
They call these cigarettes?

67
00:02:52,505 --> 00:02:55,175
They don't stain my fingers,
my hair smells like hair,

68
00:02:55,258 --> 00:02:57,718
and what do I stub out
in my scrambled eggs?

69
00:02:57,802 --> 00:03:00,432
Sure, it's got the nicotine,
but where's the tar?

70
00:03:00,513 --> 00:03:02,223
Where's the stab from every breath

71
00:03:02,307 --> 00:03:04,177
that reminds me I'm alive?

72
00:03:05,977 --> 00:03:08,857
No smoke detector! Let's roll!

73
00:03:08,938 --> 00:03:10,438
(both grunt)

74
00:03:18,656 --> 00:03:19,656
Wait, wait.

75
00:03:19,741 --> 00:03:22,331
Turn on the faucet
so no one'll get suspicious.

76
00:03:25,955 --> 00:03:27,365
(explosion)

77
00:03:27,457 --> 00:03:30,037
(smoke detectors beeping)

78
00:03:30,835 --> 00:03:32,665
Aha! I gotcha!

79
00:03:32,754 --> 00:03:34,804
-(beeping stops)
-You can't resist smoking in the house

80
00:03:34,881 --> 00:03:37,051
any more than I can resist
drinking in the car.

81
00:03:37,133 --> 00:03:38,843
-What happened?
-I don't know.

82
00:03:38,927 --> 00:03:40,637
The water caught on fire.

83
00:03:40,720 --> 00:03:42,310
(gasps)

84
00:03:42,388 --> 00:03:45,308
And now I banish you from paradise.

85
00:03:45,391 --> 00:03:48,811
I'm glad I never bothered to learn
which one of you is which.

86
00:03:48,895 --> 00:03:51,975
Please, show some compassion
for two good people

87
00:03:52,065 --> 00:03:54,145
who just can't stop smoking.

88
00:03:54,234 --> 00:03:55,904
Hmm... hmm.

89
00:03:55,985 --> 00:03:58,485
I know just the place.

90
00:03:58,571 --> 00:04:01,491
-(tires screech)
-(coughing)

91
00:04:01,574 --> 00:04:03,744
(both sniffing)

92
00:04:03,826 --> 00:04:05,866
Oh! (shudders)

93
00:04:05,954 --> 00:04:07,584
Tobacco!

94
00:04:07,664 --> 00:04:10,044
(both chuckling excitedly)

95
00:04:10,124 --> 00:04:12,004
(loud inhaling, exhaling)

96
00:04:13,253 --> 00:04:14,883
Who needs Paris?

97
00:04:14,963 --> 00:04:17,093
This is our City of Lights!

98
00:04:17,173 --> 00:04:19,433
♪ ♪

99
00:04:23,930 --> 00:04:26,270
Flaming tap water.

100
00:04:26,349 --> 00:04:28,849
I saw something about that
in a documentary.

101
00:04:28,935 --> 00:04:31,055
Sad. Sad.

102
00:04:31,145 --> 00:04:33,605
Sad. Sad. Sad. Sad.

103
00:04:33,690 --> 00:04:35,650
Sad. Sad. Sad.

104
00:04:35,733 --> 00:04:37,693
Cute. (gasps) This one!

105
00:04:37,777 --> 00:04:39,237
{\an8}<i>MALE NARRATOR:</i>
<i>In this rural community,</i>

106
00:04:39,320 --> 00:04:41,110
{\an8}<i>hydraulic fracturing, or fracking,</i>

107
00:04:41,197 --> 00:04:42,447
{\an8}<i>was greeted as a windfall.</i>

108
00:04:42,532 --> 00:04:44,532
(crowd cheering)

109
00:04:44,617 --> 00:04:47,537
<i>By pumping high-pressure liquid</i>
<i>into underground shale deposits,</i>

110
00:04:47,620 --> 00:04:49,460
<i>fracking releases natural gas,</i>

111
00:04:49,539 --> 00:04:52,379
<i>but can lead to devastating</i>
<i>environmental consequences.</i>

112
00:04:53,584 --> 00:04:54,714
(whooshes)

113
00:04:54,794 --> 00:04:58,804
Yep, used to be you could try
burning your water all day

114
00:04:58,881 --> 00:05:00,131
and nothing would happen.

115
00:05:00,216 --> 00:05:03,296
Henry, did you remember
to turn off the Slip 'N Slide?

116
00:05:03,386 --> 00:05:04,596
(children laughing)

117
00:05:04,679 --> 00:05:07,019
-(explosion)
-(screaming)

118
00:05:07,098 --> 00:05:09,808
Well, I... reckon not.

119
00:05:09,892 --> 00:05:12,312
I think someone is fracking
under our neighborhood.

120
00:05:12,395 --> 00:05:14,225
And I know who.

121
00:05:14,314 --> 00:05:17,194
It's you<i>,</i> Mr. Texan.
Oil wasn't enough--

122
00:05:17,275 --> 00:05:19,815
now you're going after
our natural gas.

123
00:05:19,902 --> 00:05:23,492
Aw, now,
ain't nothing natural about gas.

124
00:05:23,573 --> 00:05:26,833
If you can't dance in it,
I ain't drilling for it.

125
00:05:26,909 --> 00:05:30,579
I don't do this for the money,
it's the dancing.

126
00:05:30,663 --> 00:05:33,423
It's always been the dancing.

127
00:05:34,417 --> 00:05:36,997
(whooping and laughing)

128
00:05:40,715 --> 00:05:42,925
-(both sigh)
-All right!

129
00:05:43,009 --> 00:05:44,929
BART: Oh, man.

130
00:05:45,011 --> 00:05:47,061
He made us watch him dance
for three hours,

131
00:05:47,138 --> 00:05:48,968
and he really only has one move.

132
00:05:49,057 --> 00:05:51,347
If someone was fracking
in our neighborhood,

133
00:05:51,434 --> 00:05:52,694
wouldn't we know it?

134
00:05:52,769 --> 00:05:55,519
Maybe a satellite picture
will give us a clue.

135
00:05:55,605 --> 00:05:58,855
Hmm, this is clearly a fracking site.

136
00:05:58,941 --> 00:06:00,691
How are they keeping people away?

137
00:06:00,777 --> 00:06:02,947
(wind whistling)

138
00:06:03,029 --> 00:06:06,199
-Aw, it's a terrific sport--
-Shh!

139
00:06:10,078 --> 00:06:13,498
This whole building is just a facade
for a drilling operation.

140
00:06:15,291 --> 00:06:16,831
Indeed it is.

141
00:06:16,918 --> 00:06:20,458
Evergreen Terrace is built atop
a massive shale deposit.

142
00:06:20,546 --> 00:06:23,506
Think of it--
all that poor natural gas

143
00:06:23,591 --> 00:06:26,471
trapped underneath
your shanties and lean-tos.

144
00:06:26,552 --> 00:06:29,012
Smithers, give these two brats
what they deserve

145
00:06:29,097 --> 00:06:31,057
for sticking their noses
in my business.

146
00:06:31,140 --> 00:06:32,270
(both groan)

147
00:06:33,935 --> 00:06:35,265
(Lisa groans)

148
00:06:35,353 --> 00:06:38,363
Stopping Mr. Burns may be beyond
the power of an eight-year-old girl

149
00:06:38,439 --> 00:06:40,399
with a book report due on
<i>Beezus and Ramona,</i>

150
00:06:40,483 --> 00:06:42,573
but I know someone who can help--

151
00:06:42,652 --> 00:06:45,822
<i>the first female</i>
<i>Speaker of the State Assembly,</i>

152
00:06:45,905 --> 00:06:47,815
<i>a politician</i>
<i>who would never ignore</i>

153
00:06:47,907 --> 00:06:49,697
<i>a fellow environmentalist in need,</i>

154
00:06:49,784 --> 00:06:52,754
<i>my hero, Maxine Lombard.</i>

155
00:06:53,871 --> 00:06:55,501
(gasps)

156
00:06:56,582 --> 00:07:00,342
Charge the electric limo--
we're going to Springfield.

157
00:07:00,420 --> 00:07:01,670
What about your cool-down period?

158
00:07:01,754 --> 00:07:03,424
What about it?!

159
00:07:05,591 --> 00:07:08,011
Lisa! Motorcade!

160
00:07:09,345 --> 00:07:12,265
Assemblywoman Lombard!
You got my e-mails!

161
00:07:12,348 --> 00:07:14,768
I'll go anywhere, anytime,

162
00:07:14,851 --> 00:07:17,271
to defend our precious Bay Area values.

163
00:07:17,353 --> 00:07:19,363
(gasps) Terrible!

164
00:07:20,523 --> 00:07:21,903
Just shocking.

165
00:07:21,983 --> 00:07:24,363
Does anybody have a baby
we can hold near the flames?

166
00:07:24,444 --> 00:07:26,244
I guess I do.

167
00:07:26,320 --> 00:07:27,740
(sighs)

168
00:07:27,822 --> 00:07:29,322
I'm gonna hit this Mr. Burns

169
00:07:29,407 --> 00:07:32,077
with a politician's
most powerful weapon--

170
00:07:32,160 --> 00:07:34,950
an invitation to a committee hearing.

171
00:07:35,037 --> 00:07:38,827
{\an8}Mr. Burns, do you admit
that you illegally pump

172
00:07:38,916 --> 00:07:41,286
{\an8}toxic chemicals into the groundwater

173
00:07:41,377 --> 00:07:43,127
{\an8}below Evergreen Terrace?

174
00:07:43,212 --> 00:07:44,712
(indistinct whispering)

175
00:07:44,797 --> 00:07:46,627
I... don't recall.

176
00:07:46,716 --> 00:07:48,006
Mr. Burns!

177
00:07:48,092 --> 00:07:50,552
Have you no regard
for the life and health

178
00:07:50,636 --> 00:07:52,556
of your fellow human beings?

179
00:07:52,638 --> 00:07:54,178
(indistinct whispering)

180
00:07:54,265 --> 00:07:56,015
I... don't recall.

181
00:07:56,100 --> 00:07:59,400
You can't drill underneath people's homes
without their permission.

182
00:07:59,479 --> 00:08:01,809
As chairwoman
of this Committee on Energy,

183
00:08:01,898 --> 00:08:04,278
Natural Resources,
and Blimp Safety,

184
00:08:04,358 --> 00:08:07,988
your fracking operation
is hereby shut down.

185
00:08:08,070 --> 00:08:09,660
(groans)

186
00:08:09,739 --> 00:08:11,369
I demand to see that

187
00:08:11,449 --> 00:08:15,079
capitalism-castrating suffragette
this instant!

188
00:08:15,161 --> 00:08:16,871
You haven't bested me.

189
00:08:16,954 --> 00:08:19,504
I will find a way to shatter that shale.

190
00:08:19,582 --> 00:08:21,382
What makes men like you
think you can do

191
00:08:21,459 --> 00:08:22,999
whatever you want to our planet?

192
00:08:23,085 --> 00:08:25,125
Maybe the planet wants a strong man

193
00:08:25,213 --> 00:08:27,383
to take her by the hand and lead her.

194
00:08:27,465 --> 00:08:29,215
You don't know
what the planet wants.

195
00:08:29,300 --> 00:08:31,180
Oh, and I suppose you do?

196
00:08:31,260 --> 00:08:34,010
The planet wants to be
protected and nourished

197
00:08:34,096 --> 00:08:35,716
and maybe even...

198
00:08:35,806 --> 00:08:37,476
Kissed.

199
00:08:37,558 --> 00:08:39,018
(both moan)

200
00:08:39,101 --> 00:08:40,391
Mwah!

201
00:08:40,478 --> 00:08:42,858
♪ ♪

202
00:08:46,234 --> 00:08:48,444
Wait a minute,
I'm not having a stroke, am I?

203
00:08:48,528 --> 00:08:50,198
No. Am I?

204
00:08:50,279 --> 00:08:52,529
-I don't think so.
-Oh, good.

205
00:08:52,615 --> 00:08:55,365
♪ ♪

206
00:09:05,878 --> 00:09:07,258
(both gasp)

207
00:09:07,338 --> 00:09:08,458
-You!
-Me?

208
00:09:08,548 --> 00:09:10,128
(Burns shudders)

209
00:09:13,678 --> 00:09:16,348
This was all a mistake--
an impulsive...

210
00:09:16,430 --> 00:09:18,270
-Reckless...
-...knee-buckling...

211
00:09:18,349 --> 00:09:21,809
-...spat-snapping...
-...Spanx-shredding mistake.

212
00:09:21,894 --> 00:09:25,404
-(sighs) Oh, it was great.
-(chuckles) Best I've ever had.

213
00:09:25,481 --> 00:09:27,531
And that includes...

214
00:09:27,608 --> 00:09:28,938
Nellie Taft.

215
00:09:29,026 --> 00:09:32,276
So, Monty, shall we find a way
to continue this...

216
00:09:32,363 --> 00:09:34,283
purely passionate affair?

217
00:09:34,365 --> 00:09:36,025
But you're a softhearted liberal!

218
00:09:36,117 --> 00:09:38,197
And you're a hard-hearted capitalist.

219
00:09:38,286 --> 00:09:40,906
Enemies by day, lovers by night.

220
00:09:40,997 --> 00:09:42,867
MAXINE: Mmm... mwah!

221
00:09:42,957 --> 00:09:44,917
Now, get out of my office.

222
00:09:45,001 --> 00:09:47,131
As soon as I collect my things.

223
00:09:47,211 --> 00:09:49,761
Uh, derringer, sword cane,

224
00:09:49,839 --> 00:09:53,129
derringer cane, sword derringer--
all right, it's all here.

225
00:09:53,217 --> 00:09:55,337
If I want to resume fracking,

226
00:09:55,428 --> 00:09:56,888
I have to buy the mineral rights

227
00:09:56,971 --> 00:09:59,681
for every single parcel of land
in Evergreen Terrace.

228
00:09:59,765 --> 00:10:01,725
To win people over,
I'll need a salesman

229
00:10:01,809 --> 00:10:05,099
whose folksy facade
masks a deep gusher of greed.

230
00:10:07,189 --> 00:10:08,819
Hmm?

231
00:10:11,736 --> 00:10:13,646
(chuckles)

232
00:10:15,239 --> 00:10:16,869
Congratulations, Simpson!

233
00:10:16,949 --> 00:10:19,489
You're now my chief
energy innovation marketing officer.

234
00:10:19,577 --> 00:10:20,407
Whoo-hoo!

235
00:10:20,494 --> 00:10:24,174
All you've got to do is sell fracking
to your friends and neighbors.

236
00:10:24,248 --> 00:10:25,248
Whoo-hoo?

237
00:10:25,333 --> 00:10:28,173
I don't know, "fracking" is
one of those scary Lisa words.

238
00:10:28,252 --> 00:10:30,802
Bah! Fracking produces
enough clean natural gas

239
00:10:30,880 --> 00:10:34,050
to make America independent
of sheiks, caliphs, and...

240
00:10:34,133 --> 00:10:35,593
Scandinavians.

241
00:10:35,676 --> 00:10:37,846
Not to mention,
it doesn't create any of that awful

242
00:10:37,928 --> 00:10:40,098
worker-mutating nuclear waste.

243
00:10:40,181 --> 00:10:41,931
Homer, game starts in an hour.

244
00:10:42,016 --> 00:10:44,886
-Don't forget to set your fantasy lineup.
-Thanks, Charlie.

245
00:10:44,977 --> 00:10:47,187
Maybe fracking isn't so bad.

246
00:10:47,271 --> 00:10:49,571
Then say yes to this raise,
this promotion,

247
00:10:49,649 --> 00:10:51,479
and this flannel shirt, which says--

248
00:10:51,567 --> 00:10:53,647
"I'm not screwing you over."

249
00:10:53,736 --> 00:10:55,526
I'm not screwing you over.

250
00:10:55,613 --> 00:10:58,533
No, uh,
<i>I'm </i>not screwing you over.

251
00:10:58,616 --> 00:11:00,866
I'm not screwing <i>you</i> over.

252
00:11:00,951 --> 00:11:03,451
(crying)
I'm so proud of you, Papa.

253
00:11:04,705 --> 00:11:06,955
Some folks will tell you
that fracking's no good,

254
00:11:07,041 --> 00:11:08,711
but what they don't tell you is,

255
00:11:08,793 --> 00:11:11,633
hydraulic fracturing creates jobs.

256
00:11:11,712 --> 00:11:13,552
And all those new workers
are gonna want

257
00:11:13,631 --> 00:11:17,221
to spend their earnings
buying what you're selling-- beer.

258
00:11:17,301 --> 00:11:18,971
Authentic Italian food.

259
00:11:19,053 --> 00:11:20,973
Useless left-handed crap.

260
00:11:21,055 --> 00:11:22,715
Magical nonsense.

261
00:11:22,807 --> 00:11:26,017
Expensive toys for grown-ups
they don't open or play with.

262
00:11:26,102 --> 00:11:27,812
Pornography and nachos.

263
00:11:27,895 --> 00:11:30,555
High-quality
Spanish-language programming.

264
00:11:30,648 --> 00:11:32,858
High-quality methamphetamines.

265
00:11:32,942 --> 00:11:36,242
Laundry, homework, pranks,
poop, poop, and poop.

266
00:11:36,320 --> 00:11:38,740
But our water was on fire.

267
00:11:38,823 --> 00:11:42,123
How could you sell fracking
for Mr. Burns?

268
00:11:42,201 --> 00:11:44,451
'Cause I've never gotten
a promotion before.

269
00:11:44,537 --> 00:11:46,157
Once I thought I had,
but it turned out

270
00:11:46,247 --> 00:11:48,367
to be a beautifully-worded firing,

271
00:11:48,457 --> 00:11:51,287
-so judge me all you want.
-I am judging you.

272
00:11:51,377 --> 00:11:53,377
-Good. Judge away.
-Judge, judge, judge.

273
00:11:53,462 --> 00:11:55,012
-Don't care. Don't care.
-Judge, judge, judge.

274
00:11:55,089 --> 00:11:56,549
-Judge, judge, judge.
-Don't care. Don't care.

275
00:11:56,632 --> 00:11:58,052
-Don't care. Don't care.
-Judge, judge...

276
00:11:58,134 --> 00:11:59,844
Pumping frack cash.

277
00:11:59,927 --> 00:12:02,387
It's a gas cash... blast?

278
00:12:02,471 --> 00:12:04,851
<i>Residents of Evergreen Terrace</i>
<i>are undecided</i>

279
00:12:04,932 --> 00:12:07,892
<i>whether to sell</i>
<i>their mineral rights to Mr. Burns.</i>

280
00:12:07,977 --> 00:12:10,187
Mr. Burns is a vampire,

281
00:12:10,271 --> 00:12:12,861
sucking the lifeblood of this town

282
00:12:12,940 --> 00:12:15,480
and lining his coffin with cash.

283
00:12:15,568 --> 00:12:19,408
Oh, Maxine, no one insults me
in a sound bite the way you do.

284
00:12:19,488 --> 00:12:23,908
Oh, Monty,
you're such a sexy little Nosferatu.

285
00:12:23,993 --> 00:12:26,043
Same time tomorrow night?
(chuckles)

286
00:12:26,120 --> 00:12:27,580
I'll bring the oxygen.

287
00:12:27,663 --> 00:12:29,873
-(quietly) Better bring two tanks.
-Hmm?

288
00:12:29,957 --> 00:12:33,287
And so, we see a clear correlation

289
00:12:33,377 --> 00:12:35,667
between industrial hydro compounds

290
00:12:35,755 --> 00:12:39,215
and water table contamination
well outside the...

291
00:12:39,300 --> 00:12:41,800
margin of error.

292
00:12:43,971 --> 00:12:45,641
Mr. Simpson, rebuttal?

293
00:12:45,723 --> 00:12:46,773
(clears throat)

294
00:12:46,849 --> 00:12:48,729
Everyone who signs over
their mineral rights

295
00:12:48,809 --> 00:12:51,769
to Mr. Burns gets $5,000.

296
00:12:51,854 --> 00:12:53,484
5,000 smackers?!

297
00:12:53,564 --> 00:12:55,864
Money is like a job
you don't even have to do!

298
00:12:55,941 --> 00:12:57,691
-(dance music playing)
-(cheering)

299
00:12:59,945 --> 00:13:02,275
<i>-Ay, dinero.</i>
-Signing Stu.

300
00:13:02,364 --> 00:13:03,624
(laughter)

301
00:13:05,034 --> 00:13:06,954
Yeah!

302
00:13:07,036 --> 00:13:10,246
